{"title_page": "Marr (automobile)", "text_new": "The '''Marr Auto Car''' was an [[automobile]] built in [[Elgin, Illinois]] by the Marr Auto Car Company from 1903\u20131904.  The Marr was a two-seat [[Runabout (car)|runabout]] with a single-cylinder 1.7L engine that was mounted under the seat. The engine is one of the first known to have featured an [[overhead camshaft]] (OHC).<ref name=\"Marr Auto Car Company\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.marrautocar.com/Marr_Auto_Car_Company/Welcome.html |title=Marr Auto Car Company |access-date=2014-05-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014000950/http://marrautocar.com/Marr_Auto_Car_Company/Welcome.html |archive-date=2017-10-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Kimes>{{cite book|last1=Kimes|first1=Beverly Rae|author-link1=Beverly Rae Kimes |first2=James H. |last2=Cox |title=Walter L Marr: Buick's Amazing Engineer|year=2007|publisher=Racemaker Press|isbn=0976668343|page=40}}</ref> The vehicle had the first tilt steering wheel, changeable speed gears on a planetary transmission and a revolutionary new [[carburetor]].  Unfortunately the plant burnt to the ground in August 1904 with 14 cars inside. Only one Marr Auto Car exists today.\n\nThe car was designed by early automobile pioneer [[Walter L. Marr]] who had worked as an engine designer for [[Buick]] in 1901 and went on to be Chief Engineer there from 1904\u20131918.\n\nAutomotive historians credit Marr and his advanced designs with the early success of [[Buick]] which was the foundation for [[General Motors]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | author = [[Georgano, G.N.]]| title = The Complete Encyclopedia of Motorcars, 1885 to Present| year = 1968}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marr (Automobile)}}\n[[Category:Defunct motor vehicle manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicle manufacturers based in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Michigan]]\n\n\n{{Veteran-auto-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Marr Auto Car''' was an [[automobile]] built in [[Elgin, Illinois]] by the Marr Auto Car Company from 1903-1904.  The Marr was a two-seat [[Runabout (car)|runabout]] with a single-cylinder 1.7L engine that was mounted under the seat. The engine is one of the first known to have featured an [[overhead camshaft]] (OHC).<ref name=\"Marr Auto Car Company\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.marrautocar.com/Marr_Auto_Car_Company/Welcome.html |title=Marr Auto Car Company |access-date=2014-05-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014000950/http://marrautocar.com/Marr_Auto_Car_Company/Welcome.html |archive-date=2017-10-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=Kimes>{{cite book|last1=Kimes|first1=Beverly Rae|author-link1=Beverly Rae Kimes |first2=James H. |last2=Cox |title=Walter L Marr: Buick's Amazing Engineer|year=2007|publisher=Racemaker Press|isbn=0976668343|page=40}}</ref> The vehicle had the first tilt steering wheel, changeable speed gears on a planetary transmission and a revolutionary new [[carburetor]].  Unfortunately the plant burnt to the ground in August 1904 with 14 cars inside. Only one Marr Auto Car exists today.\n\nThe car was designed by early automobile pioneer [[Walter L. Marr]] who had worked as an engine designer for [[Buick]] in 1901 and went on to be Chief Engineer there from 1904-1918.\n\nAutomotive historians credit Marr and his advanced designs with the early success of [[Buick]] which was the foundation for [[General Motors]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | author = [[Georgano, G.N.]]| title = The Complete Encyclopedia of Motorcars, 1885 to Present| year = 1968}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marr (Automobile)}}\n[[Category:Defunct motor vehicle manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Motor vehicle manufacturers based in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Michigan]]\n\n\n{{Veteran-auto-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1903-1904 \u2192 1903\u20131904 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marr_(automobile)"}
